rComments: Prof Farah was a professional industry expert teaching this class. I learned so much content that I can use directly in my job instead of only theory. In general the class was very helpful and filled with knowledge and practice on the latest technologies to build real products. Thank you!

Good course content, disorganized project rubrics & grading. Ensure you have a good group to work on project Don't trust what he says in lectures regarding grades, always submit best submission else expect to get a bad grade. For category E, consider another course. Attend all classes & participate in discussions.

I learned so much in this class. A lot of material related to technology and development that I have never seen before. The prof was amazing because he gave us a real world example of how technology is used

I noticed several peer reviews attacking prof Farah for being tough and unclear with expectations which I think is unfair. This being a 4th year course, it was tough for sure but was as close to a real applicable experience as possible. Prof clearly laid out the expectations at the beginning of the course and gave a lot of good examples in class.

This was a great class with lots of hands on experience. Dr Farah was excellent in giving us real world examples that we can use in future jobs. His guest lecturer was also excellent and gave great career advice. Overall excellent class and prof. Would recommend.

This was the best class I've taken in my 4 years of university, great hands on experience and learning real world skills useful after we graduate. Professor Farah was amazing both in class and answering questions later. Students who did not do well leave bad reviews but I had a great class and thank him very much!

The course itself was fun, but was very confusing and disorganized. Groups were assembled randomly and the project outline was very vague. It seemed like the professor and TA were not communicating properly and there were several issues created because of this. Lastly, I'm pretty sure it was impossible to get over 90% for each of the project parts.

The class was hard, but that's not the professor's fault. It's the university's fault for requiring them to take this course without any coding experience. Members of my team expected Dr. Farah to completely teach them Javascript and C#, but that's not really in the scope of the course... The professor obviously knows a lot about the subject.

I think the two previous reviews are a tad unfair. He explicitly warned us about the amount of content and the self-learning needed for coding concepts. Instead of just learning the theory behind topics like cloud computing or database structure for the millionth time we were actually able to gain practical experience. Tough class but worth it.

He is arrogant and is unable to develop any proper grading scheme and then gets upset when you dont do what he wants. The class is supposed to about web technologies I dont think we learned one thing about web technologies

The prof focuses 80% on programming, which is not the purpose of this course. You simply cannot teach someone to be a Full Stack web developer in four months, by doing the equivalent of a youtube tutorial, without spending any time on the theory behind. This has no place to be in a business school. You'll be left on your own trying to code.
